         <h1>Henri Troyat, 95, a Force in French Literature </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Henri Troyat , the Russian-born French writer whose novels and biographies earned him an immense following in France and considerable recognition abroad , died here on Sunday . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 95 . <br><blue>3</blue>His death was announced by the Académie Française , of which he was a member . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Troyat was only 27 when he won the prestigious Prix Goncourt and became a permanent figure on the French literary scene , known not only for his enormous output , totaling 105 books , but also for the lucidity of his language . '' <br><blue>5</blue>He wrote a simple and clear language , a language that lasts , eternal French , '' Maurice Droun , a fellow member of the Académie Française , noted in a tribute Monday . <br><blue>6</blue>Perhaps because he avoided the experimentation of the postwar Nouveau Roman movement , led by novelists like Nathalie Sarraute , Marguerite Duras and Alain Robbe-Grillet , Mr. Troyat was never a darling of French intellectuals . <br><blue>7</blue>But French readers always embraced him . <br><blue>8</blue>As Le Figaro wrote Monday , '' the favorite writer of the French is dead . '' <br><blue>9</blue>Born in Moscow on Nov. 1 , 1911 , Lev Aslanovitch Tarassov was only 9 when his wealthy parents fled the Russian Revolution for France . <br><blue>10</blue>Already fluent in French thanks to a Swiss governess , he took the name Henri Troyat after he published his first novel at the age of 24 . <br><blue>11</blue>Three years later , in 1938 , his fifth novel , '' L'Araigne , '' won the Prix Goncourt . <br><blue>12</blue>Years later , he recalled how he forged his writing style . '' <br><blue>13</blue>I would read a paragraph of Flaubert out loud and rewrite it from memory , '' he explained , '' then , by comparing my version with the original , I would try to understand why what I had written was an affront to what I had read . '' <br><blue>14</blue>From 1940 , when he published his biography of Dostoyevsky , he completed a novel or a biography almost yearly . '' <br><blue>15</blue>A day without writing made him feel like a sinner , '' Mr. Droun wrote Monday . '' <br><blue>16</blue>For a long time he wrote standing up . <br><blue>17</blue>The carpet in front of his desk was full of holes . '' <br><blue>18</blue>Mr. Troyat also wrote a play , '' Sébastien , '' which was staged in Paris in 1946 , while several of his novels were turned into movies , including '' La Neige en Deuil , '' which was adapted for the screen in 1956 as '' The Mountain , '' starring Spencer Tracy . <br><blue>19</blue>He was elected to a seat in the Académie Française in 1959 . <br><blue>20</blue>Although he never returned to Russia and always wrote in French , Russia remained present in much of his work , notably in a stream of biographies , of Ivan the Terrible , Peter the Great , Catherine the Great , Alexander II , Nicholas II , Rasputin and other historical figures and of Russian literary giants like Tolstoy , Pushkin , Gogol , Chekhov and , most recently , Boris Pasternak . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>Alexander II</m_str> (20_42) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>Russia</m_str> (20_13) 	<br><blue>3(36)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Troyat</m_str> (6_27) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (15_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Droun</m_str> (15_13) 	<m_str>the favorite writer of the French</m_str> (8_8) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (1_13) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Lev Aslanovitch Tarassov</m_str> (9_10) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (9_17) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Troyat</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_11) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_18) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_20) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (3_12) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Troyat</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (18_23) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_7) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_4) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_9) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_28) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (20_19) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_3) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (4_42) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_17) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (14_7) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_12) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (7_6) 	<m_str>Alain Robbe-Grillet</m_str> (6_24) 	<br><blue>4(3)</blue>: <m_str>Monday</m_str> (5_33) 	<m_str>Monday</m_str> (8_5) 	<m_str>Monday</m_str> (15_16) 	<br><blue>5(1)</blue>: <m_str>Flaubert</m_str> (13_7) 	<br><blue>6(5)</blue>: <m_str>I</m_str> (13_38) 	<m_str>my</m_str> (13_25) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (13_46) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (13_31) 	<m_str>I</m_str> (13_1) 	<br><blue>7(2)</blue>: <m_str>France</m_str> (9_25) 	<m_str>France</m_str> (1_18) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>a paragraph of Flaubert</m_str> (13_4) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (13_12) 	<br><blue>9(1)</blue>: <m_str>his writing style</m_str> (12_9) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>the Académie Française</m_str> (5_25) 	<m_str>the Académie Française</m_str> (19_8) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
